HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 278
BY REPRESENTATIVES KERNER AND VILLIO
A RESOLUTION
To urge and request the Louisiana Department of Justice to conduct a comprehensive review
of the statutory framework and administrative procedures relative to electronic
monitoring in this state and to receive feedback and input from relevant stakeholders
to identify efficiencies, deficiencies, and conflicts within the existing statutory
framework that governs electronic monitoring providers and practices.
WHEREAS, the use of electronic monitoring as a tool for pretrial supervision,
post-conviction release, and the protection of victims and the public has expanded
significantly within the Louisiana criminal justice system; and
WHEREAS, the Legislature of Louisiana has enacted critical legislation to establish
initial standards for electronic monitoring providers and the reporting of noncompliance; and
WHEREAS, despite these advancements, the existing statutory framework remains
fragmented across various statutes, including R.S. 14:110.2, R.S. 15:571.36 through 571.38
and 835, and Code of Criminal Procedure Article 894.2, which may lead to inconsistencies
in enforcement and reporting and gaps in oversight; and
WHEREAS, a uniform and practical set of guidelines and procedures is necessary
to ensure the integrity of electronic monitoring data, the prompt reporting of violations to
law enforcement, and the effective registration and inspection of electronic monitoring
providers; and
WHEREAS, feedback from stakeholders within the criminal justice system and a
comparative analysis of the regulatory models utilized in other states and jurisdictions would
assist Louisiana in developing a more robust framework for the permitting, regulation, and
oversight of electronic monitoring providers and technology.
